{
  "texts": [
    "It is generally recognised that purely technical solutions cannot be given (Le Bui & Noble, 2020; Wachter, 2021).",
    "One issue in particular arises from the statistical nature of ML reasoning.",
    "If ML driven algorithms are considered as epistemic resources that help us to improve understanding and/or make better predictions, then the statistical nature of ML de facto prevents groups underrepresented in the data from contributing to this epistemic resource on an equal ground to dominant groups (Gebru et al., 2021), simply because they are not equally captured in the data sets used to train the predictive algorithms, or because the quality of the data pertaining to them is not adequate, due to biased data gathering or reuse practices (Leonelli et al., 2021).",
    "This effectively can be regarded as an instance of unjust hermeneutical marginalisation, in that it constitutes a situation of unequal hermeneutical participation (Fricker, 2016, p.163).",
    "The second set of epistemological concerns relates to the way in which algorithmic profiling affects us as epistemic agents through influencing our capacity for reasoning and understanding."
  ]
}